summary: I mean... it must be so lonely to be the only two immortal beings on earth for basically eternity-- they socialize and they'll...
question: I mean... it must be so lonely to be the only two immortal beings on earth for basically eternity-- they socialize and they'll always have each other, but a child... it would make life exciting, and fill it with love, and give them someone to take care of that they'll never have to watch grow old and die! They just want a FAMILY the same way any parents might, but it's so much more when as a couple they're the only union of their kind, when they've practically become (1/2)
answer: (2/2) their own thing over time! They’re more alike than they are like other angels and demons… a child that’s like the two of them would be someone else to share their experience of earth with, someone who will grow up to be like them, to talk to and share things with and know. Someone who will always be their baby, even after thousands of years, but like… by then, also a person they can have meaningful conversations with!

question: Top 5 Good Omens moments?
answer:
Wow…top five is hard. I’ll give you them in no particular order just so I don’t play favorites. 😊

1) The Other Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse. That scene had me rolling and I can’t wait to watch it.

2) Magician!Aziraphale having so much fun with cheap magic he learned only to be heckled by bratty rich kids (meanwhile, Crowley is pretending he doesn’t know him he’s just a waiter that’s all nothing more).

3) When Wensleydale confirmed that anything said by David Attenborough is true. (That’s my son, y'all.)

4) Anathema only having sex with Newt just cuz her ancestor said so then getting back to business.

5) “The point is… dolphins.” This is the line that won me over and I knew I was going love the shit out of this book!

summary: “I don’t see why it’s taken thousands of years to sort out.” “That’s because the people trying to sort it out were men,” said...
body:
“I don’t see why it’s taken thousands of years to sort out.”

“That’s because the people trying to sort it out were men,” said Pepper, meaningfully.

“Don’t see why you have to take sides,” said Wensleydale.

“Of course I have to take sides, said Pepper. “Everyone has to take sides in something.”

Adam appeared to reach a decision.

“Yes. But I reckon you can make your own side.”

 - Neil Gaiman, Terry Pratchett, Good Omens
